WEBVTT

00:00:00.119 --> 00:00:54.738
<v Narrator> Welcome to Echoes Through Time, the podcast where Leo, our curious time traveler, crosses centuries to engage history's most consequential figures. Today, he ventures to 1943, straight into the wolf's lair, Adolf Hitler's fortified command post on the Eastern Front. This conversation spans deep into the dictator's twisted worldview, linking his era's ambitions to modern events, such as the war in Ukraine, populist surges in politics, conflicts in the Middle East, and much more. This extended episode aims to illustrate how intolerance, propaganda, and power lust endure across ages. Prepare for a sobering journey. We find ourselves in a snowy forest in East Prussia, early 1943. The bitter cold grips the evergreen trees, concealing a network of bunkers and barbed wire. Beyond these fortifications lies the infamous Wolfsschanze, Hitler's nerve center for directing the Wehrmacht. The atmosphere is tense, marked by the smell of diesel fumes, stale cigarette smoke, and the distant thunder of artillery on the Eastern Front.

00:00:54.738 --> 00:00:54.978
<v Leo> (wind blowing) Herr Hitler, my name is Leo. I've come from a time decades after this war you're waging. I know this must sound unusual, but I'd like to learn about your views and share glimpses of the future to see how you respond.

00:00:54.978 --> 00:01:06.358
<v Adolf Hitler> The future? Ach, I've been told strange reports by my guards about someone appearing from nowhere. But speak if you have matters you wish to address. Meine Zeit ist knapp. I am leading this war with unshakeable resolve.

00:01:06.358 --> 00:01:39.019
<v Leo> I understand. I'll be direct. In my era, your name symbolizes genocide, tyranny, and devastation. The Holocaust, the ravaging of Europe, and the ideology you pushed remain etched in history as cautionary lessons. Does that matter to you?

00:01:39.019 --> 00:03:04.419
<v Adolf Hitler> Lost? Germany has lost? This is... unexpected. But I predicted the victors would demonize everything I fought for if we failed. So, while I'm shocked at this outcome, I'm not surprised by your characterization. Had we prevailed, as I was certain we would, we would have reshaped the narrative and cast ourselves as saviors of Western civilization. The future's judgment means nothing. I see no reason to cower under what you claim to be "modern morality."

00:03:04.419 --> 00:03:20.158
<v Leo> All right then. Let's talk first about your worldview. You often reference living space in the East, Lebensraum. Modern parallels are drawn to expansionist actions by world leaders today. For instance, Russia's invasion of Ukraine.

00:03:20.158 --> 00:03:47.038
<v Adolf Hitler> Russia, an invader? Heh, how ironic. I invaded them in 1941 because I despise Bolshevism and see Slavic lands as resources for Germans. If, in your era, Russia does the invading, that suggests they apply similar might to claim territory. It confirms my belief that strength is decisive. Whether they are right or wrong is secondary to me. War is about power. Always has been.

00:03:47.038 --> 00:04:05.318
<v Leo> You realize that in my day, such an invasion is condemned internationally. Nations levy sanctions, mobilize alliances, and call it a violation of sovereignty. Some compare it to your aggression toward Poland in 1939 or your thrust into the Soviet Union in 1941.

00:04:05.318 --> 00:04:27.879
<v Adolf Hitler> Condemnations? Words. If no one stops you, condemnation is toothless. Poland fell swiftly to us in 1939. Frankreich did too the next year. Had we not been overextended later, we might have solidified everything. So I remain unmoved by talk of condemnation. Nations will always act in their self-interest.

00:04:27.879 --> 00:04:48.798
<v Leo> Let's shift to something else. In my era, there's a global power shift. United States is often seen as a dominant force, but there's also China rising quickly. Economically, technologically, things you couldn't have envisioned. How do you react to hearing that the world isn't simply about European powers dominating?

00:04:48.798 --> 00:05:23.218
<v Adolf Hitler> China? The East? Interesting. In my day, Japan is the notable Asian power allied with us. If China emerges as a rival or superpower, it underscores that geopolitics never remains static. New challengers appear. Older nations adapt or fade. Deutschland, under my leadership, intended to dominate Europe and then overshadow the Anglo-Saxon world. If we had succeeded, perhaps we would have contended with China eventually. That your era sees these changes is natural. Power accumulates wherever the population and industrial base grows strong.

00:05:23.218 --> 00:05:47.959
<v Leo> In 2023, leaders do not openly advocate racial conquest like you do. However, there are populist and nationalist politicians, some in Europe, some in the Americas, using rhetoric about restoring national greatness, limiting immigration, et cetera. Many say they're resurrecting the style of your propaganda. Thoughts?

00:05:47.959 --> 00:06:21.199
<v Adolf Hitler> Your modern environment must still be rife with anxieties. People feel threatened by outsiders, disappointed by elites. So, a forceful speaker promising revival can harness that. I cultivated resentment toward Versailles, the economic collapse, perceived Jewish influence. If modern figures do the same, they exploit the same fundamental discontent. Whether they do it in my name or shun comparisons, the principle is identical. Gather the people around a unifying grievance, name the culprit, promise restoration of pride.

00:06:21.199 --> 00:06:51.639
<v Leo> One example from my time is a businessman named Donald Trump, who rose to the presidency in the United States in 2016. He had no political experience, but won by promising to make America great again. Many accused him of scapegoating immigrants, especially Mexicans, and targeting Muslims with travel bans. Others saw him simply as a patriotic populist, standing against globalism. He isn't a genocidal figure like you, but do you see any parallel with your approach to mobilizing the masses?

00:06:51.639 --> 00:07:34.879
<v Adolf Hitler> This Trump figure, interesting. I know nothing of him. But from your description, he clearly understood what I mastered in the 1930s. He took advantage of popular frustration, singled out enemies, immigrants, foreign religions, and fueled national pride with this "make America great again" slogan. That is a tactic I'm well-acquainted with. It stirs the masses, galvanizes them against perceived threats. Whether he was more moderate than myself is not my concern. The mechanism is the same. That such methods found success in America, which now fights against me, suggests that fear and a longing for strong leadership remain universal, even decades after my time.

00:07:34.879 --> 00:07:50.459
<v Leo> A crucial difference: In modern democracies, we have checks and balances, independent courts, free press, and civil liberties that your regime systematically crushed. Doesn't that hamper the ability of any would-be authoritarian to repeat your path?

00:07:50.459 --> 00:08:22.598
<v Adolf Hitler> Potentially, ja. But democracy can be manipulated from within. Remember, I rose legally, becoming Reichskanzler. Then, with the Reichstag fire and the Enabling Act, I neutralized dissent,... checks and balances crumble fast if a crisis or fear is large enough. So if your modern societies cannot handle crises, be it terrorism, economic collapse, pandemic, they might accept authoritarian measures in the name of security. That's how these systems fail from inside.

00:08:22.598 --> 00:08:37.118
<v Leo> In my era, we saw a global pandemic, COVID-19, which indeed caused economic strife and social panic. Authoritarian leaders capitalized on it to consolidate power. Do you see that as a typical root? Any crisis can become a lever.

00:08:37.118 --> 00:09:07.096
<v Adolf Hitler> Absolutely. A crisis stokes fear, and frightened people often embrace a strong hand. We used economic chaos in the early 1930s, the Great Depression, to rally the jobless and humiliated Germans to our cause. If a modern pandemic or financial crash hits, similar vulnerabilities arise. The question is whether your systems are robust enough to withstand that temptation. I would wager they are not.

00:09:07.096 --> 00:09:32.096
<v Leo> Shifting to another topic. You promoted an aggressive form of eugenics, sterilizing or killing those deemed unfit, including disabled Germans in the T4 program. Today, scientific understanding and ethical standards generally abhor that. But with advances in genetics, we face ethical debates, like designer babies or gene editing. Do you see any link to your ideas?

00:09:32.096 --> 00:10:06.256
<v Adolf Hitler> My regime sought racial purity, not subtle improvements. We believed certain categories of people burdened society and diluted the Aryan stock. If modern genetics allow more refined selection or editing, then it can be used to strengthen a population. The moral outcry is typical sentimental weakness. I see a parallel. Society grapples with who decides which traits are desirable. In my time, I was perfectly willing to decide that on behalf of the folk, though many found it monstrous.

00:10:06.256 --> 00:10:24.177
<v Leo> That attitude is precisely why your T4 euthanasia program is seen as a precursor to the Holocaust, systematic mass murder. In the future, your name is inextricably linked to genocide. How do you justify murdering so many innocents for an ideal of racial purity?

00:10:24.177 --> 00:10:47.177
<v Adolf Hitler> I do not accept they were innocent if they undermined the vitality of the Reich. Our ethos demanded a healthy, unified folk. Those who weakened it, whether physically, mentally, or through race, were obstacles. I believed removing them was essential to strengthen the nation. That is my logic, even if your era finds it monstrous.

00:10:47.177 --> 00:11:10.537
<v Leo> Yes, most of us certainly find it monstrous. Another extremely relevant point, the Holocaust also targeted Jews specifically. After World War II, many survivors moved to what became Israel. Today, Israel is a significant power, an internationally recognized Jewish state with high-tech industry and a robust military. How does that strike you?

00:11:10.537 --> 00:11:37.417
<v Adolf Hitler> (speaks in German) . I detested the notion of them organizing with global backing. If they have indeed formed a strong country, it suggests that we failed to destroy their influence. They used the aftermath of the war to gain sympathy and land, correct? In my eyes, that only confirms their cunning. I am outraged by the concept, but it aligns with what I know about Jewish survival instincts.

00:11:37.417 --> 00:11:51.777
<v Leo> And ironically, the resilience became part of the universal condemnation of your genocide. The establishment of Israel was partly driven by the world's horror at what you did. So you inadvertently propelled their cause. Any reaction to that historical twist?

00:11:51.777 --> 00:12:13.996
<v Adolf Hitler> It is indeed ironic. Had we succeeded, that state would never exist. That future stands upon my defeat, so it does not surprise me they capitalized on the moral shock. My only regret from your perspective is that Deutschland did not achieve final victory, thus preventing such an outcome. But regret is useless now.

00:12:13.996 --> 00:12:33.057
<v Leo> Returning to Europe. In my era, the European Union formed to ensure economic cooperation, peace, and the avoidance of another large-scale conflict. Germany is a leading democracy within this union, ironically pushing for unity with former adversaries. Does that sound impossible to you?

00:12:33.057 --> 00:13:01.136
<v Adolf Hitler> A union of European nations with Germany in a peaceful alliance? (speaks in German) . My entire stance was that Germany must dominate, not unify on equal terms. Yet if the continent stabilizes this way, it might be a path to prosperity. I suspect that means the Germany of your time abandoned my racial premises and militaristic drive. They chose comfort over conquest. How disappointing.

00:13:01.136 --> 00:13:14.496
<v Leo> Yes, modern Germany is quite different. Democratic, multicultural, deeply remorseful for the Nazi past with memorials to Holocaust victims. This transformation is widely admired.

00:13:14.496 --> 00:13:35.136
<v Adolf Hitler> Admired by those who embrace weakness perhaps. They prefer guilt and apology to ambition. Mein Deutschland was about forging destiny, not lamenting. Obviously, they've repudiated me. That was inevitable if they lost. It sickens me to hear of this Germany that wallows in shame rather than glory.

00:13:35.136 --> 00:14:06.996
<v Leo> Let's talk about something that doesn't exist in your time, social media. Imagine if every citizen had a small device that allowed them to instantly see messages, images, and videos from anyone in the world. These digital platforms let people share their thoughts with millions in seconds. Leaders can bypass newspapers and radio to speak directly to followers. Ordinary citizens can organize or spread ideas without government approval. If such technology had existed in your era, how would you have used it?

00:14:06.996 --> 00:14:56.856
<v Adolf Hitler> (speaks in German) . Technology is difficult to fathom. A device in every hand? Propaganda reaching millions instantly without filters? Joseph Goebbels would have been astounded by such capability. We invested heavily in radio networks and carefully staged our rallies. But what you describe would have transformed our approach entirely. The ability to speak directly to every German, to show them images and messages under our complete control, I'm genuinely surprised by how powerful this sounds. We could have responded to events immediately, crushed dissent before it spread and created a perfect system of loyalty. I find myself envious that your era's leaders possessed such tools. The Reich could have been secured far more efficiently with such power at our disposal.

00:14:56.856 --> 00:15:14.836
<v Leo> In fact, disinformation online is a huge concern. Conspiracy theories, extremist ideologies all circulate swiftly. Some supporters of white nationalism even brandish Nazi symbolism. So your legacy, ironically, still infects certain corners of the internet.

00:15:14.836 --> 00:15:37.057
<v Adolf Hitler> Such devotion from modern admirers is not surprising. The seeds of my ideology might resonate with some who yearn for a strong identity or scapegoat. If they can spread it freely, that's powerful. But if your societies remain vigilant, they might contain it. The question is always how resolutely an establishment fights extremist views.

00:15:37.057 --> 00:15:54.657
<v Leo> Yes. Many nations regulate or remove hateful content. It's an ongoing battle. Another modern phenomenon, climate change, a global crisis. Nations debate how to reduce carbon emissions. Does the concept of global cooperation for an environmental cause surprise you?

00:15:54.657 --> 00:16:33.623
<v Adolf Hitler> Climate change? I can't say I ever considered such an issue. How strange to hear of it. My concerns were territory, resources, and race.... if the environment is now an international crisis requiring cooperative solutions, that suggests the planet's wellbeing transcends national boundaries. My worldview was narrower. (german) Deutschland zuerst. Deutschland allein. I'm genuinely perplexed by this concept. I suppose if environmental collapse threatens everyone, your era must unify or perish. That's an entirely different moral framework than mine. Almost unsettling to contemplate.

00:16:33.623 --> 00:16:51.524
<v Leo> Indeed. Let's pivot to your personal life. Historians in my era discovered you had a pattern of late night activity, reliance on your personal physician, Dr. Morell, possible drug use. Are you aware that future scholars label you as a possible drug-dependent leader who made erratic decisions under the influence?

00:16:51.524 --> 00:17:20.282
<v Adolf Hitler> I'm aware of Morell's injections, vitamins, stimulants, whatever keeps me energized. If that leads some future observers to call me dependent, so be it. (german) Mein Wille remains my own. War is stressful. If these concoctions help me endure the strain of constant decision-making, it's a small price. I do not believe they compromised my leadership. Any medication that fosters alertness is an asset, not a detriment.

00:17:20.282 --> 00:17:33.522
<v Leo> Sources suggest your decisions became increasingly irrational from 1943 onward, like not letting the Sixth Army retreat at Stalingrad. That turned into a huge defeat. Could your mental or physical decline have contributed?

00:17:33.522 --> 00:17:57.002
<v Adolf Hitler> My approach was always to hold ground, push forward. Retreat is an admission of defeat. The generals who advised withdrawal were too cautious. I do not see that as irrational, rather the unwavering stand I demanded. As for health, we all suffer fatigue in war. I remain convinced the greater error was not unleashing even more force earlier.

00:17:57.002 --> 00:18:14.942
<v Leo> The war is turning against you. Meanwhile, in my future, Germany is eventually split between East and West, and then reunited in 1990. People celebrate unification under democracy, not under Nazism. That must be unimaginable from your vantage point.

00:18:14.942 --> 00:18:42.843
<v Adolf Hitler> Completely unimaginable that Deutschland would be divided, then rejoined without a national socialist framework. The concept of a democratic Germany astounds me. But if you say they thrive in that arrangement, it signals that the folk found a new path after my downfall. They have forsaken my ideology. My only response is that they have become something I never intended, yet evidently stable by your account.

00:18:42.843 --> 00:19:04.643
<v Leo> Yes, quite stable and prosperous. Another vital shift, women's rights expanded significantly. Women hold high offices, lead corporations, and shape policy. Under your regime, women were largely confined to traditional roles, (german) , children, kitchen, church. Any thoughts on modern gender equality?

00:19:04.643 --> 00:19:35.143
<v Adolf Hitler> I believed a woman's highest calling was motherhood, preserving the Aryan lineage. If modern times allow them to lead nations and corporations, that deviates from our ideal of distinct gender roles. For you, it's presumably normal. To me, it indicates how thoroughly my worldview has been discarded. Whether that fosters social stability is for you to judge. In my eyes, a strong society needed disciplined men at the helm and mothers to raise future soldiers.

00:19:35.143 --> 00:19:58.982
<v Leo> It's clear you and I differ profoundly on that. Another question. Nazi Germany, advanced technology like rockets, the V2, jet aircraft, and so forth. Now, we send rockets into space, land on the moon, and operate a space station with international cooperation. Does that surprise you or does it fit the drive for innovation your regime championed?

00:19:58.982 --> 00:20:26.202
<v Adolf Hitler> We had brilliant minds such as Wernher von Braun forging rocket technology. I used it for warfare, of course. If that same innovation extends to space exploration, I see the potential. Perhaps if we had won, we'd push for cosmic achievements under our banner. The notion of nations collaborating in space is not something I'd favor. I believed in harnessing technology for German dominance, not shared humanity.

00:20:26.202 --> 00:20:43.682
<v Leo> In my era, the idea of shared humanity is significant. Nations like the US, Russia, despite tensions, and others cooperate in space. They coordinate scientific endeavors albeit with underlying rivalries. That synergy is the polar opposite of your zero sum approach.

00:20:43.682 --> 00:21:07.002
<v Adolf Hitler> (german) . It contradicts my fundamental principle that life is an eternal struggle between competing peoples. If your era values collaboration, I can only surmise you overcame some primal drives or found mutual benefit in peaceful exploration. My vantage point is that conflict remains the prime engine of progress. We differ there.

00:21:07.002 --> 00:21:20.423
<v Leo> You also mentioned primal drives. Some historians analyze your psychological profile, extreme narcissism, paranoia, potential personality disorders. Do you dispute that?

00:21:20.423 --> 00:21:44.323
<v Adolf Hitler> Unsinn. I was simply a man convinced of my historic destiny. My mood might shift under stress, but that does not make me ill. Modern psychologists love to label anything uncompromising as pathological. I say it's willpower. If I seem paranoid, it's because conspiracies do exist, like traitors or sabotage within the Reich.

00:21:44.323 --> 00:21:58.563
<v Leo> You mentioned traitors. Towards the end of your regime, some generals and officers indeed conspired against you, the July 20th plot in 1944. By my era, they're seen as heroes who tried to stop the madness. How do you perceive them?

00:21:58.563 --> 00:22:28.823
<v Adolf Hitler> They were cowards, absolute traitors. I entrusted them with high command and they plotted my assassination. I survived that bomb, punishing them severely. If they had succeeded, they'd have handed Germany to the enemy. They are no heroes to me. They betrayed their oath. I was enraged that even the officer corps was not immune to weakness. Evidently, your era romanticizes them because they cut short the war, but I see them as verräter, pure and simple.

00:22:28.823 --> 00:22:54.383
<v Leo> Yes, that's consistent with your vantage. Let's address another big modern issue, the conflict in the Middle East. You oppose Judaism vehemently. Today, Israel and nearby Arab states have decades of tensions and wars. There have been peace treaties, but new conflicts erupt. Others revolve around religious extremism, ISIS, Jihadism. Do you see echoes of your own radical approach in these extremist movements?

00:22:54.383 --> 00:23:27.163
<v Adolf Hitler> They appear to have a fanatic devotion, though with a different ideology, Islamic fundamentalism, I presume. Radical movements share certain traits, fervor, willingness to commit violence for a cause. If they harness that effectively, they terrorize established powers. The region's tension with Israel also resonates with the Jewish question, albeit from an Islamic perspective. I do not condone their aims, but I understand the driving fanaticism. War is war.

00:23:27.163 --> 00:23:40.663
<v Leo> And in that region, ironically, some fringe groups even admired your anti-Jewish stance historically. A disturbing reminder that hateful ideologies can cross cultural boundaries. It's quite complicated in the 21st century.

00:23:40.663 --> 00:24:03.623
<v Adolf Hitler> Hatred of Jews can unite unlikely parties, I suppose. I recognized that in my time, making alliances of convenience. If it aligns interests, politics can lead to improbable partnerships. The Middle East is just another stage where historical grudges fuel conflict. So I see the parallel, though the details differ.

00:24:03.623 --> 00:24:23.473
<v Leo> Back to present day Europe.There's also debate over large-scale immigration from Africa and the Middle East, partly due to war and economic hardship. Some far-right parties claim it threatens national identities. People sometimes invoke your rhetoric to denounce them or to warn about scapegoating minorities.

00:24:23.473 --> 00:24:55.113
<v Adolf Hitler> Mass immigration changing the demographics would have alarmed me greatly. I believed preserving Aryan blood and culture was paramount. If modern parties echo that alarm, it's simply the same argument, the Volk must remain distinct or it dissolves. Whether they step into the extremist realm depends on how harshly they blame or persecute these newcomers. If your society learned from me, they might crack down on hateful rhetoric, but the tension is still there, ja?

00:24:55.113 --> 00:25:18.553
<v Leo> Correct. The tension persists. Some defend multiculturalism, others fear losing identity. Let's move to another topic, your relationship with Mussolini. Fascist Italy was your ally. In my era, we also see alliances formed between authoritarian-minded leaders across countries. Do you think autocrats naturally band together?

00:25:18.553 --> 00:25:46.932
<v Adolf Hitler> They might find common ground, shared enemies, mutual interests. Mussolini was an early model of fascism. I admired his boldness, but overshadowed him once the war progressed. Similar alliances form if it's expedient, but autocrats are often suspicious by nature. Our axis was strong for a time, though we had to bail out Italian repeatedly. So yes, they can unite, but it's a partnership of convenience, never a pure trust.

00:25:46.932 --> 00:26:06.673
<v Leo> Now, in 2023, we also see alliances under stress, like NATO expanding, the EU struggling with internal disagreements, countries forming trade blocks. The world is interconnected in ways you didn't have. Does that reduce the chance of catastrophic war, or do you still believe conflict is inevitable?

00:26:06.673 --> 00:26:36.272
<v Adolf Hitler> Integration can delay or complicate war, but tension remains. Resources, power, pride, these are timeless motivators. Nations may rely on trade and diplomacy, but if threatened, they can revert to armed confrontation. Perhaps your era's entanglements create a more cautious approach. Yet, as you say, Russia still invaded Ukraine, so major war can still erupt despite all those alliances.

00:26:36.272 --> 00:26:53.633
<v Leo> Let's talk about your final days, though we're still in 1943. Historically, we know that by April 1945, the Soviets encircled Berlin, you were in your bunker, and you took your own life with Eva Braun. Did you anticipate such an end would be your fate if the war was lost?

00:26:53.633 --> 00:27:22.732
<v Adolf Hitler> So, it ends like that, in a bunker with the Soviets closing in, a grim prophecy indeed. Yet it does not entirely contradict my resolve. I have always sworn never to fall into enemy hands alive. Humiliation is worse than death. If defeat became absolute, then yes, suicide would be the final assertion of will. My path was always victory or utter destruction, all or nothing.

00:27:22.732 --> 00:27:41.512
<v Leo> Your downfall gave way to the Nuremberg trials, where top Nazi officials were prosecuted for war crimes and crimes against humanity. The concept of genocide was legally codified. Humanity recognized a new moral boundary in reaction to your atrocities. That's a huge part of your legacy.

00:27:41.512 --> 00:28:08.252
<v Adolf Hitler> So, they turned the legal apparatus into a tool to judge and condemn our leadership. Yes, if the victor set up tribunals, that is standard in any epoch. They formalized their moral outrage, calling it a crime against humanity. They have the power to do so because we lost. Remember, had we won, we would hold our own tribunals for those who resisted us. History belongs to the victor.

00:28:08.252 --> 00:28:30.553
<v Leo> True. That's an age-old pattern. However, the crimes you oversaw, the Holocaust especially, led the world to pledge Never Again. This vow is taught worldwide, yet genocides and mass atrocities have occurred since, Cambodia, Rwanda, Bosnia. It seems we still struggle to uphold that vow.

00:28:30.553 --> 00:28:56.932
<v Adolf Hitler> That suggests humans remain humans. Moral pledges can't erase underlying hatreds, nor can they stop determined leaders from committing atrocities. My regime is singled out, but mass killings are not unique in history. The difference is I systematized it with modern efficiency. If others repeat it, it shows that civilization's veneer is thin, no matter your era.

00:28:56.932 --> 00:29:15.972
<v Leo> And that's precisely why studying your actions remains crucial. Let's pivot to something many find surprising. You had a certain affection for animals, especially dogs, and you were supposedly vegetarian. How does that reconcile with your pitiless attitude toward humans you deemed inferior?

00:29:15.972 --> 00:29:40.093
<v Adolf Hitler> Animals represented purity to me. I was revolted by slaughterhouses and felt genuine fondness for my dogs. This had no contradiction in my mind. I extended compassion to creatures I found noble, but I believed entire segments of humanity were a danger to my ideal society. One can be sentimental about a dog, yet ruthless toward human adversaries.

00:29:40.093 --> 00:30:01.772
<v Leo> It's a stark illustration of how contradictory your morality seems from a modern viewpoint. Another question. You never had children. In the future, some debate arises about whether that shaped your legacy, no direct descendants, no personal family to moderate your decisions. Do you see any link between your personal isolation and your extremism?

00:30:01.772 --> 00:30:24.313
<v Adolf Hitler> (Monkey speech) My entire energy went into the movement. A family might have distracted me. I had Eva Braun, but kept her away from public politics. I lived for Germany, devoting all my passion to forging the Reich. Perhaps that contributed to my single-mindedness, but I do not regret it. The cause was paramount.

00:30:24.313 --> 00:30:42.113
<v Leo> Now, I'm curious about your opinion on the modern phenomenon of global protest movements, where ordinary people, aided by social media, can challenge governments. For instance, large-scale protests over racial justice, corruption, or climate. Would that worry you if you were in power today?

00:30:42.113 --> 00:31:11.153
<v Adolf Hitler> Worry, ja. Mass protests, if they reach momentum, could topple a regime if the state fails to respond decisively. Social media, you say, helps them organize. I'd have outlawed or controlled those platforms immediately. In mein Deutschland, we suppress dissent swiftly. No protest would last long. I can see how that might be more complicated in your interconnected age, but an authoritarian government could still block or monitor digital communication if it's determined enough.

00:31:11.153 --> 00:31:30.492
<v Leo> Which is exactly what some modern autocracies do, censoring the internet, blocking apps, controlling media. On the other hand, democracies generally protect free expression. They grapple with balancing that freedom against hate speech. You excelled at orchestrating hateful propaganda, so we remain vigilant.

00:31:30.492 --> 00:31:51.492
<v Adolf Hitler> Indeed. If they allow complete freedom, extremists exploit it. If they clamp down, they risk stifling legitimate voices. It's a dilemma. For me, it's simple. Quell any voice contrary to the state. For you, it's more nuanced. Hence your struggles with censorship debates.

00:31:51.492 --> 00:32:15.633
<v Leo> It's a complex balance indeed. Your focus was always on decisive victory, using any means necessary. That brings me to another development from the war's end, a weapon of unprecedented power, nuclear weapons. They were first used by the United States in 1945, ironically just after you fell. Had you developed an atomic bomb first, do you think you'd have used it on your enemies?

00:32:17.083 --> 00:32:40.262
<v Adolf Hitler> ... (speaks German) Without hesitation. If such a weapon had guaranteed swift victory, I would not have hesitated, especially against the Soviets or the British. It was a race. We had research teams, but we couldn't achieve it in time. If I'd possessed it, the course of the war might have altered dramatically. Morality aside, the strategic value is undeniable.

00:32:40.262 --> 00:33:00.563
<v Leo> That's chilling, but it underscores the fear that fueled the nuclear arms race post-WWII. The threat of global annihilation led to deterrent strategies. Nations realized that using nuclear weapons could end civilization. So ironically, mutual fear prevented direct war between superpowers.

00:33:00.563 --> 00:33:19.423
<v Adolf Hitler> Yes. The logic of deterrence. If both sides risked total destruction, neither dares to strike first. That is a standstill by terror, effective if precarious. We never reached that stage. But apparently, your world has lived under that shadow for decades.

00:33:19.423 --> 00:33:45.383
<v Leo> Yes. And some worry about proliferation, smaller states obtaining nukes or even non-state groups. The horror of nuclear war remains. Let's shift again. Climate, nuclear threat, pandemics. Humanity in the 21st century faces transnational issues that require collaboration. Your worldview was about conquest. Could your Reich have adapted to a crisis requiring global cooperation?

00:33:45.383 --> 00:34:10.782
<v Adolf Hitler> Unlikely. We prioritized national and racial interests. If the planet faced a calamity, we might have used it to expand or to extort concessions from weaker nations. Genuine cooperation across different races and ideologies was anathema to me. So, no. If I were in your era, I'd still view everything as a struggle. Collaboration for the greater good was never my creed.

00:34:10.782 --> 00:34:31.222
<v Leo> That difference in fundamental outlook is crucial. Let's circle back to the conversation about leadership style. Modern political science studies your oratory techniques, rallies, theatrical crescendos, scapegoating. They label it a prime example of charismatic authority. Do you see that as your greatest strength?

00:34:31.222 --> 00:34:56.362
